Text.Value: Perhaps that's more our style anyway.
Plus, if I cry any more, I'm going to run out of tears and start leaking motor oil.
A win is a win. Gortash's Netherstone is ours.
I understand. I just wish there were another way.
That's a change. Seems like world-shattering revalations are coming at us from every angle these days.
Haha! In every blister, there I'll be.

EditorData.NodeContext: Player made her laugh through her sadness

Text.Value: Ah, my love. We've been in danger since before we even met.
What about what I want? You're asking me to let you die when we could still prevent it.
I'll be the right amount of sad. Some, but not too much. Just for you.
Is it very precious to say that, despite it all, I'm... happy?
But that's not in the stars for us, my love. Ours is a short story with a few good twists - and a banger of an ending.

EditorData.NodeContext: A bit of gallows humor here. Droll, maybe even deadpan, a touch of bitterness.

Text.Value: Now! Enough tragedy. I'm not gone yet. And our schedule is packed with important heroics, isn't it.

EditorData.NodeContext: Now! Enough tragedy. I'm not gone yet. And our schedule is packed with important heroics, isn't it.

Text.Value: Ugh, I'm sorry. I don't want you to be sad. I mean, I do. But not too sad.

EditorData.NodeContext: Voice cracks

Text.Value: No. I can't. I'd rather die here in Faerûn, my home, than live in service to a devil.
Nothing out of the ordinary then.

EditorData.NodeContext: Making a joke. Hero said all she's missed is 'villains rising, heroes falling, and the apocalypse drawing nearer'.

Text.Value: Speaking of which. There's something I wanted to ask you.
You certainly are.

EditorData.NodeContext: vulnerable, wistful.

Text.Value: You know, soldier, we're so fucked. The Dark Three are trying to consume the Sword Coast, we've still got tadpoles in our eyes, and I've got a ticking time bomb in my chest.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bit of humour, but also serious. The joke is in the all-encompassing-ness of it all.

Text.Value: Of course, my love. Of course.
At least take me to see the body. I have to see it. I have to look at him one more time.

EditorData.NodeContext: She''s pissed off

Text.Value: Thanks for everything, soldier. I'm extremely glad to be in this thing together.
I missed you too. You know, I wouldn't have bothered falling in love with you if I'd known saying goodbye would be so hard.

EditorData.NodeContext: With a sigh at the top. Put-upon by her love for the player and her imminent death.

Text.Value: We still have a future. Maybe a shorter one than most, but that doesn't make it less beautiful.
You know, I think you might be right.

EditorData.NodeContext: Warmly.

Text.Value: I probably would've exploded somewhere around Scornubel, so at least your trip home would be short.

EditorData.NodeContext: gallows humor

Text.Value: You hope correctly. Had a bit of a cry and a talking-to with the gods, but I think we're square now.

EditorData.NodeContext: Player's fobbed her off a bit, so she's keeping it casual here.

Text.Value: Who's saying goodbye? I'm here.
I'm not sure I can. It'll be too hard.
Good. I know I can trust you to keep your word on that.
It wouldn't have to be forever. Just long enough for us to figure out a way to fix your engine.
I know I can count on you.

EditorData.NodeContext: a smile behind the line. Feigning seriousness.

Text.Value: Would you believe it if I said I'm all right?
Nothing important.
Now. Let's get a move on before I start crying again. At the rate I'm going, all that'll come out is motor oil.
I think about it too.
We're going to cure you before it comes to that. I just know it.
I wish I could do what you're asking. I do. But there are things worse than death. Living in the Hells is one of them. I've done it long enough to know.
I'm not sure anyone has ever been more fucked than this.

EditorData.NodeContext: Enjoying the absurdity

Text.Value: Hey, soldier. You're back.

EditorData.NodeContext: This scene is after her big dark night of the soul monologue after killing Gortash. She leaves to go to camp and be alone for a bit. When the player returns to camp, she's here, having a moment to herself. She's still raw, but is glad to see the player. If I had my way I'd have her seated for this, but we can't do it budget-wise. Maybe another way to get that sadness/ vulnerability across, like crossed arms, hand to chin, that kind of thing? I'll leave it with ye!
EditorData.logicalname: IPRD - After SoulConsumption scene - in camp only

Text.Value: All right. But if we don't, I hope I can count on you. You haven't let me down yet, and it'd be a poor showing to start now.

EditorData.NodeContext: Being a little humorous but with an edge. She really does hope she can count on the player.

Text.Value: So do I. I've done the calculus a hundred times. There's no permutation I can find that doesn't end in me dead or wishing for death.
If you're happy, I'm happy.
Wow. Gods - you're so right. And we are beautiful, aren't we. This is - it's everything.
In that case, there's something I wanted to ask you.
To make matters, worse, there's something I wanted to ask you.
I think we're just those kind of people. Exciteable, weapon-wielding fuckers with a flair for drama.
Still 'soldier' after everything we've been through, huh?
Tell me you didn't take on Gortash. Not without me. You wouldn't have.

EditorData.NodeContext: responding to the player saying they killed Gortash without her. She can't believe what she's hearing
EditorData.logicalname: Greeting - Karlach in camp when defeated

Text.Value: And yet... we're fine. In this moment, we're fine. Here I am. There you are. Breathing. Talking. Even laughing, if we want.

EditorData.NodeContext: With a deep breath.

Text.Value: Speaking of which... there's something I wanted to ask you.
Did I miss anything important?
I can't do it anymore. I'd wish for death every day. Let me go out surrounded by things I love - not things I hate.
If I had my choice, we'd do it all together. Life - a long life. And then we'd slip away one night, side by side, wrinkled and grey, warm in our bed.

EditorData.NodeContext: Recovering herself from previous node ('I don't want to leave you behind'.). Back to business by the end of it.

Text.Value: You wouldn't have had a choice. I would've pursued you to the ends of Faerûn.
This is it. This is all we have. Each other, and all the moments we have left.
I'll think of you whenever I burn my hand on a hot stove.
I don't want to leave you behind. Not ever.

EditorData.NodeContext: Player said they're scared of being left behind by Karlach after she dies. This breaks her heart. She might even well up or cry here.

Text.Value: Will you stay with me? When it's time. For me to go.

EditorData.NodeContext: Vulnerable, asking the player to be by her side when it's time for her to die.

Text.Value: Ah, honey. I hope you miss me, but not too much. You have a gift in front of you: A whole life. You have to savour it. Promise?
It's the least you could do.

EditorData.NodeContext: She''s pissed off

Text.Value: Did I miss anything meanwhile?

EditorData.NodeContext: Fairly casual

Text.Value: Of course I'll be there, Karlach. Whatever you want.
No chance of that now, is there? Great. Fantastic.

EditorData.NodeContext: She''s pissed off

Text.Value: If I can do it, you can do it. We're in this thing together, you know. If you wanted an easy time of it, you should've given my head to those 'paladins' of Tyr way back when.
It happened faster than I realised. I had no choice.
I haven't given up, Karlach. We still might be able to fix your engine.
Thanks for everything, darling. I love you. A lot.
Gods, I've changed. I used to hamstring pit fiends for fun. Look at me now.

EditorData.NodeContext: In reaction to the player calling her 'precious'

Text.Value: Very precious indeed.
Old habits. Did I miss anything while I was off having a sulk?

EditorData.NodeContext: Being self-deprecating, but she doesn't actually feel she was sulking. She's very grounded here, hence her humour shining through.

Text.Value: We can talk about that later. I'm more concerned about you.
I can't be happy when the woman I love is in danger.
I promise I will.
I can't believe this. You knew what this meant to me. Or you should have, anyway.

EditorData.NodeContext: She''s pissed off

Text.Value: I've been worried about you. Are you all right?
Sorted yourself out, I hope?
I've considered it. Believe me, I have. But it would take Zariel all of a minute to suss me out and force me back into the Blood War.
I'm sorry, Karlach. I know you wanted to face him yourself.
Yeah, despite my best efforts. I kept trying to flop over and give up, but Karlach just won't let me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bit of a joke., Player asked her if she's ok, and she is, but still.

Text.Value: Hopefully this little misstep has taught you a thing or two about decision-making.
I'm trying to stay here, now, alive, while I can. But it's like my mind is whittled down to the black hole that should've been our future.

EditorData.NodeContext: Quiet sweetness

Text.Value: Very fair. Maybe after we've sorted one or two of the life-ending calamities staring us down.
Thank you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sincere, heartfelt, a little verklempt. The player has just agreed to be with her when she dies, no matter what. She's about to change the subject and go back to being merry.

Text.Value: Maybe. But I think... I think the gods are trying to show me my fate. And I think I'm ready to look at it.

EditorData.NodeContext: Telling the player she's ready to accept that she's going to die.

Text.Value: As it is, you're stuck loving an in-progress tragedy with a time bomb for a heart. Decisions, decisions.
This is all well and good, but I can't pretend there isn't a solution here. You could go back to Avernus and live.
Not really. But I missed you.
I think I can do anything if you're there. Even die.

EditorData.NodeContext: Very vulnerable, but warm

Text.Value: Villains rose, heroes fell, and the apocalypse drew nearer.
This is it. This is all I have. This life, and all the moments I have left here.
Karlach, would you ever consider going back to Avernus? Just for a while, just to buy yourself more time.
It's a nice idea, but I'm not there yet.
Fuck your Netherstone.

EditorData.NodeContext: She''s pissed off

Text.Value: I know what you mean. I'm scared of you leaving me behind.

Synopsis: Party defeats Gortash and after the soul consumption scene when she goes to camp. Also addreses if Karlach was at the camp at the moment.
